\par Born 1925 in Oldham, Lancashire.  Sole ambition was to be a pilot in RAF.  Father Chief of Detective Police in Oldham.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid14889180 Raymond}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672  left }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid919843 Oldham Grammar School}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid919843 at 16. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid919843\charrsid13904672 Disliked everything about Oldham, miserable, dirty, Northern town.  Although it did have a decent library.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid919843  W}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 
orked in aircraft instruments factory and studied electrical engineering at night.  Joined Air Training Corps.  Sent by RAF for short university course (economics, air navigation, etc) in Cambridge in 1943.  Then five years in RAF.  Missed war action}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid919843 , but s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 ent to Germany to trace the fate of missing air crews.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid13904672 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid919843 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid919843\charrsid13904672 Few family in Oldham, just his mother's brother.  Father's family from Preston.  Not part of a kinship network.  His ambition was to escape.  
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16078451 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 Returned to Cambridge 
and switched to anthropology at suggestion of college Senior Tutor.  Had previously liked Butterfield's history lectures.  No intention of becoming an academic, but after gaining a double first it was difficult to avoid.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16078451 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 Cambridge anthropology then not ve
ry stimulating.  Professsor was J. H. Hutton of Indian Civil Service, had conducted the Indian census.  Most influential person was John Peristiany, Greek, theoretical, who later went to Oxford, and G. I. Jones, former West Africa District Commissioner.  
Things changed when Hutton retired.  Big fight over succession, Evans-Pritchard succeeded in pressing for Meyer Fortes against antisemitic conservatives.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16078451 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 Only }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid919843 spent six months studying }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 
with Meyer Fortes.  Friendly, quiet, expected hard work, quite an influ
ence on him.  Fortes had a hard time getting established, but in time he transformed the department.  He brought in Edmund Leach and Rio Fortune.  Jack Goody and Kathleen Gough were his students.  Fortes had worked in West Africa and his Tallensi books we
re the model for detailed fieldwork.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16078451 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid919843 Went o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 
ff to British Guiana with only six months postgraduate preparation.  The idea then was that you were the instrument, and you had better get on with it; don't worry about how to do it, just do it.  Set off in banan
a boat.  Spent three weeks in Jamaica at the new Institute of Social and Economic Research, learning about West Indian history and society.  Met Lloyd Braithwaite and Elsa Goveia.  Also met Edith Clarke, who was from a prominent Jamaican planting family, 
had gone as a secretary to England, knew Malinowski, and was chosen for the West Indies Social Survey.  She had resources rather than ideas.  M. G. Smith was then still researching in Africa.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16078451 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 Chose Guiana through suggestion of Colin Rosser, who had been in
 the Indian Army and was interested by the Indian population there.  Government also interested in Guyana as a possible place for Jewish settlement.  Funded by Colonial Social Science Research Council.  Intended as a broad study of social change rather th
a
n just on kinship, and focussed on the African Guianese population. Guiana was in the middle of the political transition to independence. Kinship was one key focus, especially since Simey was arguing in was a key problem in the West Indies, but in his the
sis it is discussed alongside politics and race (and land tenure).  His published book from the thesis cuts out much of this.  
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid16078451 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16078451 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 In the thesis he argues that kinship is not disorganised and a key cause of poverty: as Simey had suggested, and later on, in th
e USA, Moynihan, or William J. Wilson and the Poverty Project.  It's a constantly recurring idea.  Influence of Meyer Fortes in showing with the Ashanti, who are matrilineal, that kinship can be structured without being centred on the nuclear family; whic
h Murdoch and other Americans were then proposing was a universal human institution.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16078451 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 First researched for a year in Hope Town.  Then back to Jamaica for three months, and wrote an initial paper.  Then returned and worked three months for comparative purpos
es in two African }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid919843 Guianese villages, Den Amstel (\lquote Better Hope\rquote ) and Dartmouth (\lquote Perseverance\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 ).
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16078451 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 Describes finding Hope Town, recommended as very backward and very African.  Found a house through talking with Village Chairman, helped by Chinese storekeeper
.  Sanctioned by District Commissioner.  No running water, no electric light, but a very happy year.  Had a cook, who was sister of Jimmy Johnson, Village Overseer.  Food ordered from Booker's in Georgetown and sent down by train.  Visiting agricultural i
nstructor helped him to develop a kitchen garden.  Kids came a lot, would make ice cream for them.  Lots of social life and dances.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16078451 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 Made a lot of friends, and knew almost everybody out of 1,800 in the village.  He collected a lot of the information himself
, but also employed helpers for the census and for the land tenure information was helped by the Village Overseer, who kept all the land records.  
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16078451 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 Periodic regular cadastral surveys.  Land system in Jamaica is English, in Guiana Roman Dutch.  Many planta
tions had been bought be ex-slaves.  Each village was supposed to maintain its own dykes and drainage canals, but many villages along West Coast Berbice (where Hope Town was) were then under water for most of the year.  The ex-slaves had a difficult time:
 
they had tried growing export crops like arrowroot, but were under pressure from the planter class, who wanted them as labour.  The Central Government organised them into villages, and tried to get them to pay rates to maintain the drainage system, but th
ey did not have enough cash, so paid labour rates. This somet}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid919843 imes worked, sometimes didn't}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16078451 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 There was a form of family land, but}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid919843  it was}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672  not called this.  Hope Town was bought by ex-slaves in 1840 and divided into about 30 fa}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid919843 mily shares, each with land at \lquote first depth\rquote }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 
, next depth, etc.  Roman Dutch Law allowed joint inheritance.  Some pressure periodically from the Government to divide into individual ownership.  Reluctance to sell out to non-village families: if a man married in, the land remained in his w
ife's name.  Discusses this in thesis, and paper in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 Social and Economic Studies.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16078451 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 African population did not develop commercial agriculture.  They worked on the sugar plantations for money in season, and grew vegetables for local use.  East Indians by cont
rast q}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid919843 uickly started to grow rice and}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 
 raise cattle for sale.  But Africans would not sell them land, and only more recently have begun }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid919843 to grow rice for sale.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16078451 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 East Indians were encouraged to stay when indentures were finished and they were entitled to a re
turn passage, so given land as an inducement.  They chose to grow rice because it is easier to cultivate than sugar, and they had the experience.  Their patriarchal family structure also made it easier to mobilise women and children to work in the fields.
 
 Africans had less of a rice growing tradition - although they did take it up in South Carolina - and never grew it so intensively; they would broadcast seed rather than plant seedlings by hand.  Also they wanted to escape from the regimented agricultural
 labour which seemed too}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid3814683  much}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672  like slavery.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16078451 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 Did very few genealogies at this stage.  Partly due to Fortes' influence, which he now thinks was wrong, focussed on the household structure.  Hope }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid3814683 Town people said they were all \lquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 one f}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid3814683 amily\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 
.  But it was only when he returned in 1975, that he did two things: first, document what had happened to all the people who were there in 1956; and second, collect extensive genealogies, in the villages, and also in Georgetown and in Jamaica.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16078451 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 Returned to E}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid3814683 ngland in 1953 and completed Ph}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 D in 1954.  The returned to Jamaica, to the Institute of Social and Economic Research, planning to study the East Indian population.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid13904672 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 
\par Did not think he would get work in Cambridge, so returned to Jamaica. Funded by Colonial Social Science Research Council.  By then had married his second wife Flora Tong, Guyanese, introduced to him as a Social Welfare Officer.  First wife }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid3814683 was English and}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672  had not been to Guiana.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16078451 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 Began studying East Indians in St Mary, especially in banana are
a. Had been brought in as sugar plantation labourers, and then spread out into independent cultivation.  Highly acculturated, nearly all Christians, many Seventh Day Adventists.  Interesting study, but more a preparatory exerc}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid9650410 ise, and he never wrote it up.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16078451 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid9650410 Spent one}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672  year in 1956 living in Windsor Forest}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid9650410 
 in Guyana}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 .  A different experience.  More prosperous, but still no electric light or running water.  Lots of rats from the rice.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid9650410 They }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 had a baby: eldest son was just three months when they went.  They were
 more incorporated, involved in weddings and rituals, everybody wanting to hold the}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid9650410 ir}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672  child.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16078451 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 Fascinated by social organisation, with splits along religious lines, both between Hindu majority and the Muslims, and between Hindu sects.  Big debates.  Religio
n used in status struggles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16078451 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 
Collected material on domestic organisation, land ownership, and rice cultivation and costs - a separate paper on the last.  Also information on landholdings by villagers outside the village.  Returned to Jamaica and wrote a lo
ng report (which he has), and published some articles, but regrets that he did not publish a sizeable work on that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16078451 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 When he had been in Jamaica preparing for this study of East Indians in Guyana, there was a committee of the Royal Anthropological Institute set up by }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid14889180 Raymond}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672  Firth to encourage industrial sponsorship}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4666213  for \lquote 
