\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 Invited to Ghana to replace
 Kofi Busia, politician and head of Sociology, who had fled from Nkrumah; appointed as Senior Lecturer until the Acting Head Sincalir Drake left.  There three years.  Department expanded from eight students to a hundred.  Ghana then very interesting as th
e
 first independent African colony, Nkrumah dynamic, lots of visitors.  Finally became chair when Sinclair Drake left, but at this point Nkrumah started to take over the university, firing faculty, student demonstration put down by the army.  So then decid
ed to return to Jamaica.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid16078451 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 While in Ghana some research on birth and death registrations, hoping to understand more about kinship, and differences between matrilineal and pa}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid4666213 trilineal peoples.  Unpublished}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 
, apart from some articles on demography.  Doug Freelander took the data.  The differences are mainly at the level of property inheritance.  The matrilineal system in Ghana does not marginalise men, because they do inherit, but a man's heir is his sister'
s son rather than his own son.  In fact in Ghana the men sit talking and drinking beer while the women do all the work.  Had earlier read studies on matrilineal people, not only the Akhan in Ghana but also Indians in Malabar.
