Did not look at how the Indian and African villages related.  Hope Town thought of itself as African, but there were Indians living there, and Indian landowners at the edge of the village.  Much intermarriage with the neighbouring Ind
ian village.  But tended to be discounted.  Only realised this later, through genealogies.  Windsor Forest was similar, an East Indian rice village, but many Africans living there.  In periods of conflict, driven out of the villages.  Some of the mixed co
u
ples were protected by their neighbours.  Especially up Demerara River, where more intermarriage, local vigilante groups protected mixed couples.  In Windsor Forest even the Sanatandam priest had black relatives.  Barbadian indentured servants had come th
ere in the 19}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\super\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid13904672\charrsid13904672  C.  But few true mixed villages.
